Certainly! Below is an HTML code snippet that creates an unordered list of synonyms for the word "pungent." Each synonym is a clickable link that redirects to its definition on a dictionary website like Merriam-Webster.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Synonyms for Pungent</title>
    <style>
        ul {
            list-style-type: none;
            padding: 0;
        }
        li {
            margin: 5px 0;
        }
        a {
            text-decoration: none;
            color: #007BFF;
        }
        a:hover {
            text-decoration: underline;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Synonyms for "Pungent"</h1>
    <ul>
        <li><a href="https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/sharp" target="_blank">Sharp</a></li>
        <li><a href="https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/biting" target="_blank">Biting</a></li>
        <li><a href="https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/acrid" target="_blank">Acrid</a></li>
        <li><a href="https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/penetrating" target="_blank">Penetrating</a></li>
        <li><a href="https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/tart" target="_blank">Tart</a></li>
        <li><a href="https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/piquant" target="_blank">Piquant</a></li>
        <li><a href="https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/caustic" target="_blank">Caustic</a></li>
    </ul>
</body>
</html>
```

In this example, each synonym is linked to its definition on the Merriam-Webster website. The links open in a new tab due to the `target="_blank"` attribute. You can modify the links to point to your preferred dictionary website if necessary.
